Wash and dry all produce. Adjust rack to upper position and preheat oven to 450 degrees. Cut @sweet potatoes{2} into ½-inch-thick wedges (like steak fries). Toss on a #baking sheet{} with a drizzle of @olive oil{1%tsp} and @cumin{1%tsp} (we'll use the rest later). Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Roast in oven until tender and crisped, ~{20-25%minutes}.

Cut @lemon{1} into quarters. Mince @garlic{1%clove} (use the other as you like). Finely chop @parsley{¼%oz}. Halve @grape tomatoes{4%oz}.

In a #small bowl{}, stir together parsley, a pinch of garlic, a squeeze of lemon, @olive oil{3%tbsp}, and @cumin{½%tsp} (save remainder for the chicken). Season generously with salt and pepper. Add more garlic and lemon to taste.

Pat @chicken breasts{12%oz} dry with a #paper towel{}. With your hand on top of one chicken breast, cut ¾ of the way through middle, parallel to cutting board, stopping before you slice through completely. Repeat with other chicken breast. Open each up like a book and season all over with salt, pepper, and remaining cumin.

Heat a drizzle of @olive oil{1%tsp} in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Add chicken and cook until no longer pink in center, ~{3-4%minutes} per side. Meanwhile, in a #large bowl{}, whisk together @honey{1%tsp} (we sent more), a big squeeze of lemon juice, and a large drizzle of @olive oil{1%tbsp}. Add tomatoes and @mixed greens{2%oz} and toss to coat. Season with salt and pepper.

Divide chicken between plates and drizzle with chimichurri. Serve with sweet potato wedges and salad on the side.

> Chimichurri is an Argentinian herb sauce that pairs well with most proteins. Here, it complements pan-seared chicken breasts with roasted sweet potato wedges and a fresh salad.